nced** binary search tree with the same node values*. If there is more than one answer, return **any of them**.\n\nA binary search tree is **balanced** if the depth of the two subtrees of every node never differs by more than `1`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1382-balance-a-binary-search-tree/1382-balance1-tree.jpg]]\n\nInput: root = [1,null,2,null,3,null,4,null,null]\nOutput: [2,1,3,null,null,null,4]\nExplanation: This is not the only correct answer, [3,1,4,null,2] is also correct.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/1382-balance-a-binary-search-tree/1382-balanced2-tree.jpg]]\n\nInput: root = [2,1,3]\nOutput: [2,1,3]\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 10⁴]`.\n\n- `1 <= Node.val <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/balance-a-binary-search-tree/","problemName":"Balance a Binary Search Tree","problemNumber":1382,"problemSlug":"balance-a-binary-search-tree","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":1382,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Greedy","Sorting","Heap (Priority Queue)"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two integers `n` and `k` and two integer arrays `speed` and `efficiency` both of length `n`. There are `n` engineers numbered from `1` to `n`. `speed[i]` and `efficiency[i]` represent the speed and efficiency of the `i^(th)` engineer respectively.\n\nChoose **at most** `k` different engineers out of the `n` engineers to form a team with the maximum **performance**.\n\nThe performance of a team is the sum of its engineers' speeds multiplied by the minimum efficiency among its engineers.\n\nReturn *the maximum performance of this team*. Since the answer can be a huge number, return it **modulo** `10⁹ + 7`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 2\nOutput: 60\nExplanation: \nWe have the maximum performance of the team by selecting engineer 2 (with speed=10 and efficiency=4) and engineer 5 (with speed=5 and efficiency=7). That is, performance = (10 + 5) * min(4, 7) = 60.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 3\nOutput: 68\nExplanation:\nThis is the same example as the first but k = 3. We can select engineer 1, engineer 2 and engineer 5 to get the maximum performance of the team. That is, performance = (2 + 10 + 5) * min(5, 4, 7) = 68.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 4\nOutput: 72","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= k <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `speed.length == n`\n\n- `efficiency.length == n`\n\n- `1 <= speed[i] <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= efficiency[i] <= 10⁸`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Greedy","Sorting","Heap (Priority Queue)"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given two integers `n` and `k` and two integer arrays `speed` and `efficiency` both of length `n`. There are `n` engineers numbered from `1` to `n`. `speed[i]` and `efficiency[i]` represent the speed and efficiency of the `i^(th)` engineer respectively.\n\nChoose **at most** `k` different engineers out of the `n` engineers to form a team with the maximum **performance**.\n\nThe performance of a team is the sum of its engineers' speeds multiplied by the minimum efficiency among its engineers.\n\nReturn *the maximum performance of this team*. Since the answer can be a huge number, return it **modulo** `10⁹ + 7`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 2\nOutput: 60\nExplanation: \nWe have the maximum performance of the team by selecting engineer 2 (with speed=10 and efficiency=4) and engineer 5 (with speed=5 and efficiency=7). That is, performance = (10 + 5) * min(4, 7) = 60.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 3\nOutput: 68\nExplanation:\nThis is the same example as the first but k = 3. We can select engineer 1, engineer 2 and engineer 5 to get the maximum performance of the team. That is, performance = (2 + 10 + 5) * min(5, 4, 7) = 68.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 4\nOutput: 72\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= k <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `speed.length == n`\n\n- `efficiency.length == n`\n\n- `1 <= speed[i] <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= efficiency[i] <= 10⁸`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-performance-of-a-team/","problemName":"Maximum Performance of a Team","problemNumber":1383,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two integers `n` and `k` and two integer arrays `speed` and `efficiency` both of length `n`. There are `n` engineers numbered from `1` to `n`. `speed[i]` and `efficiency[i]` represent the speed and efficiency of the `i^(th)` engineer respectively.\n\nChoose **at most** `k` different engineers out of the `n` engineers to form a team with the maximum **performance**.\n\nThe performance of a team is the sum of its engineers' speeds multiplied by the minimum efficiency among its engineers.\n\nReturn *the maximum performance of this team*. Since the answer can be a huge number, return it **modulo** `10⁹ + 7`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: n = 6, speed = [2,10,3,1,5,8], efficiency = [5,4,3,9,7,2], k = 2\nOutput: 60\nExplanation: \nWe have the maximum performance of the team by selecting engineer 2 (with speed=10 and efficiency=4) and engineer 5 (with speed=5 and efficiency=7). That is, performance = (10 + 5) * min(4, 7) = 60.","type":"code"},{"seque